ound game.</p><p class=3D"sc-9a00e533-0 eZyhnA">However, that doesn't mean =
that all the big numbers have been thought of, expressed, written down=E2=
=80=A6 or even represented by computers.</p><p class=3D"sc-9a00e533-0 eZyhn=
A">First let's climb up the ladder of numbers directly beyond those used in=
 day-to-day life. In news headlines, the biggest numbers =E2=80=93 of <a ta=
rget=3D"_self" href=3D"https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-50504151" class=
=3D"sc-f9178328-0 iCaRzc">national debt</a>, for instance =E2=80=93 tend to=
 be expressed in the trillions. But there's a hiererchy of ever-bigger numb=
ers that come afterwards, the names of which rarely get mentioned. It start=
s with quadrillions, quintillions, sextillions and so on. A quadrillion (th=
e US version) has 15 zeroes, a quintillion has 18, and a sextillion has 21.=
